  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Emergency Education Project for Crisis Affected Most Vulnerable  Host community and IDP Learners, in Lower Shabelle region</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The project targets 9 primary schools namely Ayuub, Ali Banadir, Gaywarrow, Buulo Mareer, bakaal, KM50, Eel munye, Shalanbood and Tima &#x201B;Adde Primary schools in Merka, Qoryooley, Kurtunwarey, amp Wanlaweyn districts of Lower Shabelle region affected by crisis (conflict, 2017 drought and 2018 floods) in South West State. AYUUB in response to emergency affected learners in the larger Somalia has proposed this project to mainly retain 4227 learners (2305 boys) and 110 teachers (44 female) and 63 CECs (31 female) at school in mitigating the case of high school dropout rate following the 2017 drought and floods issues that accompanied the crisis. The project will strive to achieve the outcome of enhansing quality learning opportunities through provision of quality Teaching and Learning Materials in 9 public primary schools, water provision in 2 schools and complimentary food provision in 6 public primary schools targeted to improve the physical and mental growth of learners.  Teacher incentives to 110 teachers and head teachers spread over the 9 targeted schools will contribute to improving the quality of life for teachers and their families. 
Protection aspects will provide protective learning environments for most vulnerable learners through Training of 63 CECs on child protection issues including PSS, DRR spread over the 9 targeted schools, Rehabilitation of classrooms in 4 classrooms in Ali Banadir Primary schools which were previously destroyed during civil unrest to attract the many IDPs children to enroll, rehabilitate 4 separate gender appropriate latrines, 3 water tanks for three schools and build the capacities of  CECs to better manage school resources with a focus on finding sustainable solutions.
The project will train  63CECs on management of school resources to better address Education concerns brought about by the drought in the schools that AYUUB has been supporting with the help of volunteer teachers all of whom were once learners in the same schools and now giving back to the community where they were brought up. This will also act as entry points to address other emergency related concerns like AWD outbreaks in schools, school health screening and aid provision challenges.</narrative>
  </description>
